Series I: New York University , 1950-1999

langmaterial

English

Scope and Content

Series I contains materials dating from between 1950 and 1999, created through Larry Spruch's activities as a professor of Physics at New York University. The series is divided into three subseries.

Subseries A: Course Materials contains lecture notes, problem books, quizzes, and exams from the undergraduate and graduate level Physics courses which Spruch taught. It also contains news clippings and other materials used in Spruch's popular Physics and Society course, which discussed the relationship between physics and current events and was geared toward non-Physics majors. Some preliminary examinations for the Ph.D. in Physics dating from between 1967 and 1990 are included in the series. Finally, a few folders of materials from NYU courses which Spruch may have audited, such as Literature of Modern Ireland, are present in Subseries A.

Subseries B: Faculty and Administrative Affairs contains materials related to Spruch's non-teaching duties at NYU. As such, it includes memoranda and other materials reflecting the activities of the Physics department and the larger NYU faculty. It also contains documentation of Spruch's activities while on sabbatical from NYU.

Subseries C: Student Theses and Dissertations includes drafts and final copies of theses and dissertations which were created under Spruch's supervision, or in which Spruch took an interest.

Series II: Correspondence, 1941-2005

English

Scope and Content

Series II is largely made up of Larry Spruch's professional correspondence, as well as some personal correspondence. The majority of the correspondence in the Larry Spruch Papers is located in this series, though the occasional letter may also be found in Series IV and Series V, as Spruch filed correspondence about certain articles or projects alongside the other related materials.

Series III: China-U.S. Physics Examination and Application (CUSPEA) Program, 1980-1987

langmaterial

English

Scope and Content

Series III contains materials from Larry Spruch's participation in the China-U.S. Physics Examination and Application (CUSPEA) program in the 1980s. Drafts and final copies of exams in English and Physics which Spruch helped to develop are included, as are Spruch's correspondence with other CUSPEA-affiliated physicists and the administrators of the program. A diary and ephemera from Spruch's 1985 trip to China, which was taken under the auspices of the program to interview prospective graduate students, are also included in this series.

Series IV: Professional Materials, 1927-20041950-2002

langmaterial

English

Scope and Content

Series IV encompasses various aspects of Larry Spruch's participation in the international community of physics scholars. The series is divided into four subseries.

Subseries A: Manuscript and Research Proposal Referrals contains Spruch's reviews of manuscripts submitted by other physicists for publication in various academic journals, as well as reviews of a handful of research proposals. These materials are not open to researchers.

Subseries B: Works by Other Physicists contains published articles and manuscripts to which Spruch did not personally contribute, but in which he seems to have taken a professional interest. Nearly all of these materials are heavily annotated by Spruch, and many are also accompanied by his own calculations of problems discussed in the texts, or his correspondence with the authors. The arrangement system of this subseries is somewhat complex because it maintains some aspects of the collection's original order. For example, while Spruch seems to have generally grouped materials of this type together by author and arranged the folders in alphabetical order by the author's last name, some materials were also grouped topically or by the publication in which they appeared. The materials in this subseries date from between 1927 and 2004, though the bulk of them date from between 1950 and 2002.

Subseries C: Conferences, Workshops, and Seminars contains materials from professional gatherings, many of them international, in which Spruch participated or simply attended. These materials include notes on presentations given by Spruch or other physicists, event programs, correspondence with event organizers and participants, and documentation of Spruch's travel to and from the events. Especially well-represented in this series are materials from the Aspen Center for Physics, a summer research program in Aspen, Colorado in which Spruch participated frequently. The materials in this subseries date from between 1956 and 2003.

Subseries D: Awards and Honors contains materials related to some—though not all—of the numerous awards and honors which Larry Spruch received throughout his career. Many of the materials included in the series are related to a website created by the NYU Physics department in 2000 in honor of Larry Spruch. Spruch's Brooklyn College Alumni Award of Honor in this subseries dates from 1967, though the other materials date from the latter part of his career, between 1984 and 2001.

Series V: Research, 1949-2004

langmaterial

English

Scope and Content

Series V contains materials generated by Larry Spruch and his collaborators while conducting and publishing research in theoretical particle physics and astrophysics. It is divided into four subseries. Subseries A: Published contains examples of Spruch's and his collaborators' work in its final, published format, usually as reprints or preprints. Drafts and earlier versions of many of these materials are also included in Subseries B: Drafts and Unpublished Writings. Subseries C: Notes and Calculations contains the least formal documents in this series. It is largely composed of notes and calculations on various issues in physics, some of which reappear in more polished form in Subseries A and B. Many of the materials in Subseries C, in particular, may be obscure in meaning to researchers without extensive backgrounds in physics, as their contents are expressed mathematically rather than in grammatical English. Finally, Subseries D: Research Proposals and Contracts contains proposals and contracts for grants to fund research in which Larry Spruch participated. Most of the materials in the series concern funding from the National Science Foundation; however, the Army Research Office and the Office of Naval Research are also represented.

Series VII: Personal Materials, 1948-2002

langmaterial

English

Scope and Content

Series VII contains materials related to Larry Spruch's personal life, rather than his work as a physicist. Many of the materials in this series are maps, souvenirs, and other tourist ephemera gathered by Spruch during his travels around the world. Though much of that travel was the result of Spruch's participation in the conferences, seminars, and workshops (see Series IV: Subseries C), he made time to explore the area as well. Other materials in the series are related to Spruch's personal interests, which included theatre and progressive politics. The materials in this series date from between 1948 and 2002.

Series VIII: Sports Puzzles, 1965-19961972-1996

langmaterial

English

Scope and Content

Series VIII contains materials related to another of Larry Spruch's hobbies, writing puzzles. A copy of 21 Astounding Science Quizzes!, written with his wife, Grace Marmor Spruch, is included in this series. However, the rest of the materials relate to the development of a manuscript of sports-themed puzzles which Spruch continued to expand and refine between 1965 and 1996. The manuscript remains unpublished.
